----

== Research Overlap ==

=== Core Research Question ===

**How far can fact-checking be pushed toward low-resource operation using smaller specialized models — without losing verdict reliability?**

Recent results show this is feasible:

|=Evidence|=Finding
|ViClaim (EMNLP 2025)|550M encoder matches or beats 3B-7B decoders on claim detection (F1=0.90 vs o3-mini F1=0.78)
|SIGIR 2024|Fine-tuned XLM-RoBERTa (0.743 F1) beats GPT-4 (0.624) across 114 languages
|DRAG (ACL 2025)|RAG knowledge distilled from LLMs to small models: 27.7% improvement
|AVeriTeC 2025|Shared task now requires <10B parameters and <1 minute per claim
|EdgeJury (2026)|Ensembles of 3B-8B models: 76.2% TruthfulQA, 8.4s latency

**Adjacent question: low-latency retrieval.** How to make evidence retrieval fast enough for interactive use. CheckThat! 2025 found hybrid BM25 + dense retrieval + reranking delivers strong **MRR@5**, while LLM query rewriting costs 60x inference time for poor benefit.

No prior work we have identified studies a **full multi-stage pipeline** (extraction → retrieval → debate → aggregation) while evaluating both model-capacity reduction and retrieval latency. FactHarbor offers a concrete baseline for these tradeoffs.

=== Concrete Potential Joint Research Tracks ===

|=Track|=Research question|=Entry point|=Key metrics|=First experiment
|**A. Resource-efficient screening**|Can smaller models replace large-model work in early stages without harming verdict quality?|Stage 1 + 2 screening subtasks|**F1 / Macro-F1**, latency, cost, verdict agreement|Swap one subtask for a 500M-1.5B model on a multilingual benchmark
|**B. Low-latency retrieval**|How much retrieval latency can be removed while preserving verdict-relevant evidence?|Stage 2 query generation + reranking|**MRR@5**, latency, evidence yield, sufficiency|Compare current stack with a capped hybrid pipeline
|**C. Reproducibility**|How stable are verdicts across reruns, paraphrases, and languages?|Config snapshots, neutrality harness|Truth-% spread, confidence spread, cross-language delta|DE / EN / FR / PT rerun set with normalization variants

=== Related Academic Work and Potential Partners ===

|=Area|=Key work|=FactHarbor connection|=Partnership fit
|**Claim detection**|HAMiSoN (CHIST-ERA, EUR 1.1M, 2023-2025, 26 pubs); ViClaim (EMNLP 2025 main, 17K sentences, 3 languages); CheckThat! Lab (CLEF, longest-running shared task)|Claim worthiness → Stage 1; verified claim retrieval → Stage 2|ZHAW NLP group — strongest direct overlap with FactHarbor's pipeline stages
|**Source attribution**|AFaCTA (ACL 2024, ETH): LLMs can cite wrong sources or misrepresent them|Every verdict traces to evidence items with reliability scores; grounding check (Step 5) in advisory mode|**ETH — Prof. Elliott Ash** (Law, Economics & Data Science Group). Also: e-FEVER, BallotBot (RAG). Could be partner, advisor, or co-PI.
|**Evidence quality**|DIRAS (NAACL 2025): explicit relevance definitions and calibrated scores outperform categorical approaches|Our evidence filter uses categorical //probativeValue// — DIRAS-style scoring could strengthen this|—
|**Multi-agent debate**|Climinator (UZH/ETH, 96% binary accuracy on climate claims, Mediator-Advocate framework)|FactHarbor's 5-step debate adds self-consistency, cross-provider diversity, evidence-weighted contestation — **topic-agnostic by design**|**UZH — Prof. Markus Leippold**. Now expanding beyond climate into political fact-checking with EU partners.

